"1424","1468":"1468","1466":"1466","23 March 1424":"23 March 1424","1431":"1431","about 1414":"about 1414","1474":"1474","before 1394":"before 1394","1419":"1419","Henley on Thames, Oxfordshire, England":"Henley-on-Thames, Oxfordshire, England","Ireland":"Ireland","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Stonor, Oxfordshire, England":"Stonor, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Pyrton, Oxfordshire, England":"Pyrton, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stonor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Stonor (Oxon).","2  English: occasional variant of   Stoner  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stoner","meanings":["English (Sussex): topographic name from Middle English <i>ston(e)</i> ‘stone’ + <i>-er</i>, used for someone who lived by a prominent rock or stone, or perhaps who came from a place called Stone, although this formation is more rare. See   Stone   and compare   Stoneman  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Steiner  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Stonor was born on 26 April 1394, in Pyrton, Oxfordshire, England, his father, Ralph Stonor, was 26 and his mother, Joan Belknap, was 23. He married Alice Kirby before November 1415. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 2 March 1431, in Henley-on-Thames, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 36."},"et